  "prompt": "Why am I allergic to dogs and not to cats?",
  "response": "Allergies to pets, including dogs and cats, are caused by proteins found in their skin cells, urine, and saliva. The reason you might be allergic to dogs but not cats is because the proteins that trigger allergic reactions are different between these animals. \n\nFor dogs, the common allergenic proteins are Can f 1, Can f 2, Can f 3, Can f 4, Can f 5, and Can f 6. These proteins are primarily found in dog dander (skin flakes), saliva, and urine. \n\nFor cats, the primary allergen is Fel d 1, which is mainly found in cat saliva, skin, and urine. There are also other cat allergens like Fel d 2, Fel d 3, Fel d 4, etc.\n\nIndividual sensitivity to these allergens varies from person to person, which is why someone might be allergic to dogs and not to cats, or vice versa. It's also possible to be allergic to both, or to neither. \n\nIf you are experiencing allergies, it's best to consult with an allergist who can help identify the specific allergens causing your symptoms and suggest proper management strategies.",
